This page is the "control center" for our stored procedures: record_donation and record_distribution.

We use a Tabbed Interface. One tab for incoming food (Donations) and one for outgoing food (Distributions), with a shared Live Inventory view at the bottom so we can see the database update in real-time.

1. Operations Portal Layout (OperationsPortal.jsx)

This code includes the forms needed to capture the parameters for our MySQL procedures.

2. Database Logic

FIFO Note: Under the distribution button, we added a small note about FIFO. This highlights the dbPROCS.sql logic where the record_distribution procedure uses ORDER BY expiry_date ASC to pick which batch to decrement.

SKU/Batch Correlation: The Inventory table on the right should ideally be grouped by SKU but show multiple rows for different expiry dates. This demonstrates that our database tracks batches, not just total quantities.

Procedure Mapping: The input fields map 1-to-1 with the parameters in our CALL record_donation(...) statements.

3. Integrating with GCP & Spring Boot

When we're ready to connect the frontend to the backend:

POST Request: Our React app will send a JSON object with these form fields to our Spring Boot controller.

Service Layer: Our Spring Boot service will then call the MySQL stored procedure using a JdbcTemplate or Repository call.

Error Handling: If Our trigger (trg_after_distribution_items_insert) throws an error because the stock is too low, the backend will return a 400 Bad Request. Our React form should catch this and show a red error message to the user.

4. Mapping UI to our RDBMS

This page is essentially a visual wrapper for the "People" tables in our schema:

The Switcher: Filters between volunteers, staff, donors, and beneficiaries.

Volunteers List: Demonstrates the join between users and volunteers. The "Status" pill reflects our users.status column (Active/Inactive).

The Shift Logic: we added a "Next Shift" column. In a full implementation, this would run a SELECT MIN(shift_date) from volunteer_shifts where shift_date >= CURDATE().

3. Demo

When presenting, use this page to talk about Referential Integrity:

Volunteers/Staff: Point out that while they look like separate lists, they both inherit core data (names, emails) from the users table via their shared user_id Primary Key.

Triggers: Mention that if we were to "Add a Shift" that overlaps, the database itself (not just the UI) would throw a SQLSTATE '45000' error, which the UI would then display as a "Double Booking" alert.
